Question 1.2: Why Does Variable Type Matter?

In your own words: Why do we care about whether a variable is continuous or categorical?

Your answer here:

Click to see Solution 1.2

Sample answer: Variable type determines: 1. Which summary statistics we can use (mean for continuous, mode/frequency for categorical) 2. Which visualizations are appropriate (histogram for continuous, bar chart for categorical) 3. Which statistical tests we can apply 4. How we interpret the data (categories vs.measurements)

Question 3.2: Skewness Interpretation

Look at this distribution of GDP per capita in the world dataset:

Questions:

  1. Is this distribution left-skewed or right-skewed?

Your answer:

  1. In a right-skewed distribution, is the mean greater than or less than the median? Why?

Your answer:

Click to see Solution 3.2 
# Check actual values
mean(world$gdppc, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 16326.78
median(world$gdppc, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 9863.205

Answers:

  1. This is right-skewed (has a long tail to the right)

  2. In a right-skewed distribution, the mean is greater than the median because the extreme high values pull the mean upward, but the median is resistant to outliers.

Mnemonic: The skew points in the direction of the tail!

Question 3.3: Mode

What is the mode of the following variable, and how would you find it?

# Find the mode (most common value) of states$region
Click to see Solution 3.3 
# R doesn't have a built-in mode function!
# For categorical variables, use table()
table(states$region)
## 
##     South      West   Midwest Northeast 
##        16        13        12         9
# The mode is the value with the highest frequency
# Or use sort:
sort(table(states$region), decreasing = TRUE)
## 
##     South      West   Midwest Northeast 
##        16        13        12         9

Answer: The mode is South (appears most frequently)

Definition: The mode is the most frequently occurring value in a dataset. Its most useful for categorical data.

Question 4.3: Key Components of a Plot

List and define some of the key components every good plot should have:

Your answer:

Click to see Solution 4.3

Key components of a plot:

  1. Title: Descriptive title explaining what the plot shows
  2. Axis labels: Clear labels for x and y axes with units if applicable
  3. Legend (if needed): Explains colors, shapes, or groups
  4. Appropriate scale: Axis ranges that show the data clearly
  5. Clear visual encoding: Appropriate chart type for the data

Optional but helpful: - Caption with data source - Gridlines (if they aid interpretation) - Color scheme thats accessible

Question 5.2: Variable Recoding

# a) Create a new variable in states called "high_murder" that equals 
#    "High" if murderrate > 5 and "Low" otherwise


# b) Create a new variable in world called "gdp_category" with three levels:
#    "Low" if gdppc < 5000
#    "Medium" if gdppc 5000-20000
#    "High" if gdppc > 20000
Click to see Solution 5.2 
# a) Binary recode
states <- states %>% 
  mutate(high_murder = case_when(murderrate > 5 ~ "High",
                                 TRUE ~ "Low"))

# Check it worked
table(states$high_murder)
## 
## High  Low 
##   20   30
# b) Multiple category recode
world <- world %>% 
  filter(!is.na(gdppc)) %>% 
  mutate(gdp_category = case_when(gdppc < 5000 ~ "Low",
                                  gdppc > 20000 ~ "High",
                                  TRUE ~ "Medium"))
                                 
# world$gdp_category <- ifelse(world$gdppc < 5000, "Low",
#                               ifelse(world$gdppc <= 20000, "Medium", "High"))

# or with cut():
world$gdp_category2 <- cut(world$gdppc, 
                            breaks = c(-Inf, 5000, 20000, Inf),
                            labels = c("Low", "Medium", "High"))

# Check it worked
table(world$gdp_category, useNA = "always")
## 
##   High    Low Medium   <NA> 
##     50     58     68      0

Question 5.3: Variable Transformations

# a) Create a log-transformed version of world$gdppc called gdppc_log


# b) Why might we want to log-transform GDP per capita?
# Your answer:


# c) Create a per-capita version of states$stuspend (student spending)
#    by dividing by poptotal and multiplying by 1000 (per capita in thousands)
Click to see Solution 5.3 
# a) Log transformation
world$gdppc_log <- log(world$gdppc)

# Compare distributions
# par(mfrow = c(1, 2))  # Side by side plots
# hist(world$gdppc, main = "Original GDP per capita")
# hist(world$gdppc_log, main = "Log GDP per capita")

world %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = gdppc), fill = "navy") +
  labs(
    title = "Original GDP per capita"
  )

world %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = gdppc_log), fill = "maroon") + 
  labs(
    title = "Log GDP per capita"
  )

# b) Why log-transform?
# - GDP is right-skewed; log makes it more normally distributed
# - Makes it easier to see patterns across all values
# - Helps meet assumptions for some statistical tests
# - Proportional changes become linear

# c) Per capita calculation
states$stuspend_pc <- (states$stuspend / states$poptotal) * 1000

# Check it worked
summary(states$stuspend_pc)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1536  0.8458  1.4278  3.0395  3.4125 16.1489

# a) Create a scatterplot with a line of best fit

# Your answer:
Click to see Solution 6.1

Interpretation guide: - The line of best fit shows any relationship between the x and the y variables - Positive slope = as one increases, other tends to increase - Negative slope = as one increases, other tends to decrease - Closer to 0 = weaker/no relationship

Click to see Solution 8.1
Feature R Script (.R) R Markdown (.Rmd)
File extension .R .Rmd
Main purpose Run code Create reports/documents
Contains formatted text? Only as comments Yes, markdown formatting
Output format None (just runs code) HTML, PDF, Word, etc.
Best used for Data analysis, functions Reports, homework, presentations

R Script: - Just code and comments - Run line by line or all at once - No formatted output

R Markdown: - Combines code, output, and narrative text - Knits to create polished documents - Great for reproducible reports

Section 9: Conceptual Questions

Question 9.1: Short Answer

Answer in 2-3 sentences each:

a) What is data wrangling and why is it important?

Your answer:

b) When should you use a log transformation, and what does it do?

Your answer:

c) Explain the difference between the mean and median. When might you prefer one over the other?

Your answer:

d) Why do we create visualizations instead of just looking at summary statistics?

Your answer:

Click to see Sample Answers

a) Data wrangling: The process of cleaning, transforming, and organizing raw data into a format suitable for analysis. Its important because real-world data is often messy, contains errors, and isnt structured for the analysis we want to do.

b) Log transformation: Use when data is highly right-skewed (like income, GDP). It compresses large values and spreads out small values, making the distribution more symmetric and easier to interpret.

c) Mean vs.Median: The mean is the average (sum/count); the median is the middle value. The median is better when you have outliers or skewed data because its not affected by extreme values. The mean is better for symmetric distributions and uses all the data.

d) Visualizations: They help us see patterns, outliers, and relationships that summary statistics might miss. A famous example is Anscombes Quartetfour datasets with identical means, medians, and correlations but completely different patterns visible only in plots.
